          <li class="nav__link nav__link--resume"><a href="/resume.pdf" download>resume.pdf</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>

      <!-- Post Header -->
      <section class="hero">
        <div class="powerline">
          <span class="powerline__seg powerline__seg--user">osim@dev</span>
          <span class="powerline__seg powerline__seg--path">~/blog</span>
          <span class="powerline__seg powerline__seg--cmd">cat self-service-k8s.md</span>
          <span class="cursor" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="post__meta">
          <span class="post__date">2025-11-03</span>
          <span class="post__reading-time">8 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="post__title">Building a Self-Service Kubernetes Platform from Scratch</h1>
      </section>

      <hr class="divider" />

      <!-- Post Body -->
      <article class="post__body">
        <p>When I joined the platform team, "deploying to Kubernetes" meant opening a Jira ticket, waiting for someone on infra to review your YAML, and hoping your namespace quota was right. Average time from "ready to deploy" to "running in staging": four days. That's not a platform. That's a bottleneck with a logo.</p>

        <p>Over the next eight months, we built a self-service system that got that number down to under thirty minutes. Here's how.</p>

        <h2>Start with the interface, not the infrastructure</h2>

        <p>The first mistake teams make is building the platform bottom-up: pick a service mesh, wire up the CNI, configure RBAC policies, then figure out how developers will interact with it. We flipped that. We started by asking developers one question: <em>what do you need to give us to get your app running?</em></p>

        <p>The answer was surprisingly simple. They needed to specify: a container image, the port it listens on, how much CPU and memory it needs, and which environment variables it requires. Everything else — networking, scaling, health checks, logging — should have sane defaults that they can override if they want to.</p>

        <p>So that's what we built. A single YAML file (we called it <code>app.yaml</code>) that lived in the root of every repo:</p>

        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code__comment"># app.yaml — minimal config</span>
<span class="code__key">name:</span> checkout-service
<span class="code__key">image:</span> $IMAGE
<span class="code__key">port:</span> 8080
<span class="code__key">resources:</span>
  <span class="code__key">cpu:</span> 250m
  <span class="code__key">memory:</span> 512Mi
<span class="code__key">env:</span>
  <span class="code__key">DATABASE_URL:</span> vault://db/checkout
  <span class="code__key">REDIS_URL:</span> vault://cache/checkout</pre>

        <h2>The operator that ties it together</h2>

        <p>Behind the scenes, a custom Kubernetes operator watches for <code>AppDeployment</code> CRDs generated from those YAML files. When a new one lands, the operator:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Creates the namespace (if it doesn't exist) with standard labels and resource quotas</li>
          <li>Generates the Deployment, Service, and Ingress manifests from the app spec</li>
          <li>Injects sidecar configs for logging (Fluent Bit) and metrics (OpenTelemetry collector)</li>
          <li>Resolves <code>vault://</code> references into Kubernetes Secrets via the Vault CSI driver</li>
          <li>Sets up HPA defaults based on the resource tier</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The entire operator is about 2,000 lines of Go. Not trivial, but not a monster either. The key decision was keeping it opinionated — we don't expose every Kubernetes knob, just the ones that matter for 90% of use cases.</p>

        <h2>GitOps as the deployment API</h2>

        <p>We chose ArgoCD for continuous delivery. Every merge to <code>main</code> triggers a GitHub Actions workflow that builds the image, updates the <code>app.yaml</code> with the new image tag, and opens a PR to the deploy repo. ArgoCD picks it up from there.</p>

        <p>The beauty of this approach is that the deploy repo becomes a ledger. You can <code>git log</code> it and see exactly what's running, when it was deployed, and who approved it. Rollbacks are <code>git revert</code>.</p>

        <h2>What we got wrong</h2>

        <p>Plenty. The first version of the operator didn't handle CRD schema migrations well — we had to manually patch about forty resources when we added the <code>scaling</code> field. We also underestimated how much time we'd spend on developer education. The tooling was there, but teams needed hand-holding through their first two or three deploys before they trusted it.</p>

        <p>The biggest lesson: your platform is only as good as the experience of the person using it for the first time. We added a <code>platform init</code> CLI command that scaffolds the <code>app.yaml</code> and validates it against the CRD schema before you push. First-deploy success rate went from 60% to 95%.</p>

        <h2>Where it stands now</h2>

        <p>Fifteen teams deploy through the platform daily. Most never touch a Kubernetes manifest directly. The operator handles the complexity so they don't have to. And when they do need something custom — a CronJob, a StatefulSet, an unusual networking rule — the escape hatch is clean: drop raw manifests into a <code>k8s/</code> directory and ArgoCD will apply them alongside the generated ones.</p>

        <p>Self-service doesn't mean zero-touch. It means the touch is intentional, minimal, and designed for the person doing the deploying — not the person who built the platform.</p>

        <div class="post__end">
          <span class="post__end-marker">--- EOF ---</span>
        </div>
      </article>

